CI/Build fails at Mathlib/Data/Finsupp/Defs.lean:685:9: 
error:  Finsupp.erase_idem.{u_5, u_1} simp can prove this
I don't how how to fix that except by removing the @[simp] tag before the function.

Thanks :tada:

bors merge
bors r-
Canceled.

I think you should
* add `update_erase : update (erase a f) a (f a) = f`
* reverse `erase_eq_update_zero` to `update_zero_eq_erase`

Then I'm happy.

I have been convinced otherwise in DMs.

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion rw [â† update_eq_erase, update_idem] ```

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion rw [â† update_eq_erase, â† update_eq_erase, update_idem] ```

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion rw [â† update_eq_erase, â† update_eq_erase, update_idem] ```
wouldn't the name `update_zero_eq_erase` be more explicit?
Or perhaps `erase_eq_update(_zero)` after flipping the direction?
Yes. For a surprising reason, the absence of zero doesn't disturb me in the other direction.
I've gone for reversing it then
maybe `update_update` would be a more intuitive name.
This matches `Function.update_idem`
excellent reason to stay by this name!

```suggestion
-- not `simp` as `erase_of_not_mem_support` can prove this
theorem erase_idem (f : Î± â†’â‚€ M) (a : Î±) :
```

```suggestion
theorem erase_eq_update_zero (f : Î± â†’â‚€ M) (a : Î±) : f.erase a = update f a 0 :=
```
for discoverability. I would even consider
```suggestion
@[simp]
theorem update_zero_eq_erase (f : Î± â†’â‚€ M) (a : Î±) : f.erase a = update f a 0 :=
```
Did you mean to flip the direction in that last one?
Note that there was already discussion about this in https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9316#discussion_r1437765537
Yep, sorry, I meant it flipped

```suggestion
@[simp] theorem update_erase_self (f : Î± â†’â‚€ M) (a : Î±) (b : M) :
    update (erase a f) a b = update f a b := by
```
and you should have
```
-- @[simp] maybe?
theorem update_erase_of_ne (f : Î± â†’â‚€ M) {a a : Î±} (ha : a â‰  a') (b : M) :
    update (erase a f) a' b = erase a (update f a' b) := by
```
This is called `insert_erase` on `Finset`, so I think the current name is correct.
`Finset` is a weird comparison. Surely you should rather look at `Function`? I'm looking at `Function.update_same` and `Function.update_noteq` (which are pretty bad names indeed).
Actually, your claim is wrong. `insert_erase` would correspond to `update (erase a f) a (f a) = f`.
Perhaps `update_erase_eq_update` to match the `erase_update_eq_erase` I suggest below?
That would be good, yes.
I've made that change

```suggestion
@[simp] theorem erase_update_self (f : Î± â†’â‚€ M) (a : Î±) (b : M) :
    erase a (update f a b) = erase a f := by
```
On `Finset` this is called `erase_insert_eq_erase`; shall I change to `erase_update_eq_erase`?
